abstract: >
  An autonomous AI-agent–driven cryptanalysis pipeline for the Elliptic Curve
  Discrete Logarithm Problem (ECDLP), implemented end-to-end by Anthropic's
  Claude Sonnet 4.6 / Opus 4.7 via the Claude Code interface, demonstrated on IBM
  Quantum Heron r2 hardware. Two qualitatively distinct results:
  (Phase 0, 2026-04) 22-bit (m=22) private-key recovery — six algorithmic
  steps beyond Lelli's 17-bit Q-Day Prize Round-1 winner — using
  adaptive-counting and Stern-Brocot continued-fraction lift extraction
  in the verification-filter regime; (Phase 1, 2026-05) a statistical test
  (permutation test on Hidden Number Problem d-class separation) that
  distinguishes genuine collective quantum signal from verification-filter
  recovery, and the first datapoint to pass it — on the Quantinuum H2-1
  emulator at m=3 (p≈0.0003), with IBM hardware as a negative control
  (p≈0.61, verification-filter regime). Across four platforms the signal
  tracks end-to-end circuit fidelity. Scope: the H2-1 result is on the
  emulator (noise model), not yet the physical QPU.
